WEBVTT

00:07.540 --> 00:10.500
Hi there! Welcome to
this video, where we

00:10.500 --> 00:12.220
are going to learn
about social media

00:12.220 --> 00:15.260
influencers. The goal
of the presentation

00:15.260 --> 00:17.060
is to help you
understand what

00:17.060 --> 00:20.080
influencers are and
what motivates them.

00:20.380 --> 00:23.520
In the video, firstly
, we will define what

00:23.520 --> 00:25.740
an influencer is,
then we will look at

00:25.740 --> 00:27.360
some examples of
social media

00:27.360 --> 00:32.520
influencing and what
motivates them. What

00:32.520 --> 00:36.160
is a social media
influencer? Social

00:36.160 --> 00:38.520
media influencers are
people who have built

00:38.520 --> 00:40.240
a significant
following on social

00:40.240 --> 00:42.420
media platforms and
have the ability to

00:42.420 --> 00:44.520
affect their
audience's opinions,

00:44.520 --> 00:46.800
behaviours and
purchasing decisions.

00:46.980 --> 00:50.200
What defines an
influencer? They

00:50.200 --> 00:53.700
create regular
content around

00:53.700 --> 00:57.160
specific topics or
lifestyles, and their

00:57.160 --> 00:59.380
followers trust their
opinions or enjoy

00:59.380 --> 01:01.420
their personality
enough to engage with

01:01.420 --> 01:03.460
and act on their
recommendations.

01:04.120 --> 01:06.240
Influencers typically
partner with brands

01:06.240 --> 01:08.280
to promote products
or services to their

01:08.280 --> 01:09.000
audience.

01:12.200 --> 01:15.040
Common categories are
beauty and fashion,

01:15.040 --> 01:17.380
gaming and technology
, fitness and

01:17.380 --> 01:20.100
wellness, food and
cooking, travel and

01:20.100 --> 01:23.300
lifestyle, education
and how-to content,

01:23.300 --> 01:24.920
comedy and
entertainment,

01:24.920 --> 01:26.640
parenting and family
life.

01:30.500 --> 01:32.500
Influencers typically
make money through

01:32.500 --> 01:35.100
sponsored posts.
Brands pay them to

01:35.100 --> 01:38.200
feature products.
Affiliate marketing,

01:38.200 --> 01:40.900
earning commission on
sales, ad revenue

01:40.900 --> 01:43.160
from their content,
selling their own

01:43.160 --> 01:45.620
merchandise or
products, and brand

01:45.620 --> 01:48.300
partnerships or
ambassadorships.

01:49.580 --> 01:51.460
Things to be aware of
.

01:54.800 --> 01:56.980
Unrealistic standards
and self-esteem

01:56.980 --> 02:00.640
issues. Influencers
often present heavily

02:00.640 --> 02:02.860
edited, curated
versions of their

02:02.860 --> 02:04.640
lives that can make
people feel

02:04.640 --> 02:06.800
inadequate about
their own appearance,

02:06.800 --> 02:09.380
lifestyle or
achievements. This

02:09.380 --> 02:12.520
constant comparison
can lead to anxiety,

02:12.520 --> 02:15.980
depression and body
image issues. Hidden

02:15.980 --> 02:19.580
advertising and
manipulation. Many

02:19.580 --> 02:21.380
influencers promote
products without

02:21.380 --> 02:23.840
clearly disclosing
sponsorships, making

02:23.840 --> 02:25.920
it hard for people to
distinguish genuine

02:25.920 --> 02:28.480
recommendations from
paid promotions.

02:28.480 --> 02:30.480
People may feel
pressure to buy

02:30.480 --> 02:32.720
things they don't
need or can't afford.

02:33.000 --> 02:35.900
Dangerous trends and
challenges. Some

02:35.900 --> 02:38.260
influencers promote
risky behaviours,

02:38.260 --> 02:40.700
dangerous challenges
or harmful products

02:40.700 --> 02:43.140
like extreme diets,
unregulated

02:43.140 --> 02:45.120
supplements or
potentially dangerous

02:45.120 --> 02:47.040
stunts without
considering the

02:47.040 --> 02:50.980
impact on followers.
Privacy erosion.

02:50.980 --> 02:52.680
Influencer culture
normalises

02:52.680 --> 02:55.620
oversharing personal
information online.

02:55.700 --> 02:58.480
People may mimic this
behaviour without

02:58.480 --> 02:59.980
understanding the
long-term

02:59.980 --> 03:02.160
consequences for
their privacy and

03:02.160 --> 03:05.320
digital footprint.
Parasocial

03:05.320 --> 03:08.040
relationships. Teens
can develop one-sided

03:08.040 --> 03:10.240
emotional attachments
to influencers,

03:10.240 --> 03:11.860
feeling like they're
friends when the

03:11.860 --> 03:14.540
influencer doesn't
know they exist.

03:14.920 --> 03:17.760
Inappropriate content
and values. Some

03:17.760 --> 03:20.140
influencers promote
materialism, shallow

03:20.140 --> 03:22.160
values or
inappropriate content

03:22.160 --> 03:25.060
for young audiences.
Others may exhibit

03:25.060 --> 03:28.100
problematic behaviour
, drama, conflicts,

03:28.100 --> 03:30.160
questionable ethics
that people might

03:30.160 --> 03:33.640
view as normal or
aspirational. Scams

03:33.640 --> 03:36.060
and exploitation.
People may encounter

03:36.060 --> 03:38.340
fake giveaways,
phishing schemes or

03:38.340 --> 03:39.840
influencers who
exploit their

03:39.840 --> 03:42.860
audience financially.
Some predators also

03:42.860 --> 03:45.600
pose as influencers
to gain trust.

03:46.120 --> 03:48.500
Distorted career
expectations. The

03:48.500 --> 03:50.960
glamorised influencer
lifestyle can give

03:50.960 --> 03:53.320
people unrealistic
ideas about work,

03:53.320 --> 03:55.720
success and how easy
it is to make it

03:55.720 --> 03:57.780
online, potentially
affecting their

03:57.780 --> 03:59.920
academic motivation
or career planning.